        h1("Chapter 1: Introduction"),

        h2("1.1 Background"),
        p("The rapid digitalization of global and regional labor markets has dramatically transformed how employers and job seekers interact. Traditional job portals — which primarily facilitate job listings, resume uploads, and keyword-based search — have become increasingly inadequate in meeting the demands of a competitive, skill-driven economy. Platforms such as LinkedIn, Indeed, and Rozee.pk, while widely adopted, operate on fundamentally limited paradigms: they rely on surface-level keyword matching, offer no deep semantic understanding of candidate profiles, provide minimal personalized guidance, and offer no feedback loop for unsuccessful applicants."),
        p("The recruitment industry globally processes billions of job applications annually. A significant proportion of qualified candidates are filtered out not due to genuine unsuitability, but due to linguistic variations in how skills are described — a candidate listing 'TensorFlow' may not match a job requiring 'Machine Learning,' despite the conceptual overlap. Similarly, recruiters face enormous volumes of applications with little automated intelligence to assist in objective, fair, and efficient shortlisting. The absence of explainability in AI systems used for hiring has also drawn growing scrutiny from ethicists, regulators, and applicants who deserve to understand why they were rejected."),
        p("HireAI was conceived to address these systemic deficiencies. It represents a paradigm shift from conventional job portals to what the project team defines as a Cognitive Recruitment Ecosystem — a platform that understands language semantically, ranks candidates fairly, explains its decisions transparently, and provides real-time career intelligence to all stakeholders."),

        h2("1.2 Problem Statement"),
        p("Current job portal systems fail to provide intelligent, personalized, and equitable experiences for both job seekers and employers. The specific problems identified are:"),
        bullet("Vocabulary Mismatch: Keyword-based matching systems fail when candidates use synonymous or contextually equivalent terminology for skills and experience, leading to false negatives in candidate discovery."),
        bullet("Algorithmic Bias: Automated candidate ranking systems, where they exist, lack fairness-aware mechanisms, potentially perpetuating historical biases in hiring based on gender, location, or demographic characteristics."),
        bullet("Black Box Rejection: AI systems that score or rank candidates provide no explanation to unsuccessful applicants, creating an opaque and demotivating experience while preventing candidates from improving."),
        bullet("Manual Screening Inefficiency: Employers continue to invest disproportionate time reviewing applications, with no intelligent pre-screening that accounts for holistic candidate fit."),
        bullet("Platform Fragmentation: Job seekers maintain separate profiles on multiple platforms (LinkedIn, Indeed, Rozee.pk) without a unified interface that aggregates the broader job market."),
        bullet("Absence of Career Intelligence: Existing platforms provide no skill gap analysis, personalized learning recommendations, or interview preparation support."),

        h2("1.3 Objectives"),
        p("The primary objectives of HireAI are:"),
        numbered("Develop a Semantic Intelligence Engine using an ESCO-taxonomy-based Skill Knowledge Graph to achieve 85%+ accuracy in matching synonymous skill expressions across resumes and job descriptions."),
        numbered("Implement a Fairness-Aware Ranking (FAR) algorithm using AIF360 and FairLearn to ensure demographic parity in candidate shortlisting with a ratio greater than 0.8 as per the Four-Fifths Rule."),
        numbered("Build an Explainable AI (XAI) Engine that generates counterfactual explanations for match scores, enabling candidates to receive actionable, specific feedback."),
        numbered("Develop an NLP-based Resume Analyzer with ATS scoring that provides structured feedback on resume quality in under 10 seconds."),
        numbered("Implement a Hybrid Job Discovery Engine that aggregates real-time external job listings from LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor alongside internal database jobs."),
        numbered("Integrate an AI Career Chatbot powered by GPT/HuggingFace for real-time career guidance, interview preparation, and platform navigation."),
        numbered("Deliver a complete, deployable web application serving Job Seekers, Employers, and Administrators with role-based dashboards, at zero deployment cost using free-tier cloud infrastructure."),

        h2("1.4 Scope"),
        p("HireAI encompasses the development and deployment of a full-stack web application with four primary user roles. For Job Seekers, the platform provides resume upload and ATS scoring, personalized job recommendations, skill gap analysis, application tracking, and access to the AI career chatbot. For Employers, the platform provides company profile management, AI-assisted job posting, automated candidate shortlisting and ranking, a bias audit dashboard, and recruitment analytics. For Administrators, the platform provides user management, content moderation, and system health monitoring. The platform also includes a Hybrid Job Engine providing dual-mode access to both internally posted jobs and real-time aggregated listings from major external platforms."),
        p("Out of scope for the current version are video-based AI mock interviews, salary prediction using external salary APIs, and deep integration with e-learning providers such as Coursera or Udemy (identified as future work)."),

        h2("1.5 Significance of the Project"),
        p("HireAI addresses a recognized gap in the Pakistani and global job portal market. No single existing platform combines ATS scoring, semantic skill matching, explainable AI rejection feedback, fairness-aware ranking, and external job aggregation in one product. In the context of Bahria University's Final Year Project program, HireAI represents a research-grade implementation that integrates advanced concepts from Natural Language Processing, Machine Learning, Explainable AI, and Fairness in AI — topics at the forefront of contemporary software engineering and data science research."),

        h2("1.6 Sustainable Development Goals Alignment"),
        p("HireAI directly contributes to four United Nations Sustainable Development Goals:"),
        bullet("SDG 8 – Decent Work and Economic Growth: By intelligently connecting qualified candidates with suitable employment opportunities and reducing friction in the hiring process."),
        bullet("SDG 4 – Quality Education: By providing AI-powered skill gap analysis and learning path recommendations that support continuous professional development."),
        bullet("SDG 9 – Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure: By building next-generation AI-driven digital recruitment infrastructure."),
        bullet("SDG 10 – Reduced Inequalities: By implementing bias-free, fairness-aware ranking to ensure equal opportunity in recruitment regardless of gender, location, or socioeconomic background."),

        pageBreak(),

        // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        // CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW
        // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        h1("Chapter 2: Literature Review"),

        h2("2.1 Overview of Existing Job Portals"),
        p("The online recruitment industry has matured significantly since the early 2000s. Platforms such as LinkedIn, Indeed, Monster, and regionally, Rozee.pk and Bayt.com, have established themselves as dominant intermediaries in the labor market. However, research consistently highlights that these platforms suffer from structural limitations that hinder effective matching."),
        p("LinkedIn, despite its extensive professional networking capabilities and rich profile data, does not offer ATS-style scoring, career coaching, or counterfactual feedback for unsuccessful applications. Its skill endorsement system is self-reported and unverified, limiting its utility for objective candidate assessment. Indeed operates primarily as a job aggregator with basic keyword filtering and a simple apply mechanism, offering minimal intelligence at the point of matching. Rozee.pk, the leading Pakistani job portal, functions similarly to early-generation job boards with keyword search, category filters, and manual recruiter workflows."),
        p("A common weakness across these platforms is their reliance on lexical (keyword-based) rather than semantic (meaning-based) matching. This results in high rates of false negatives where genuinely qualified candidates are filtered out due to terminological differences, and false positives where keyword-stuffed resumes achieve high rankings despite poor actual fit (Smith et al., 2023)."),

        h2("2.2 AI in Recruitment"),
        p("The application of artificial intelligence to recruitment has been an active area of both academic research and industry development over the past decade. Early approaches focused on automating resume parsing using rule-based systems and regular expressions. More recent work leverages transformer-based language models for deeper semantic understanding."),
        p("Li and Zhao (2021) demonstrated that machine learning-based resume screening could reduce hiring time by up to 50% while simultaneously improving candidate quality metrics. Their work used gradient-boosted trees on structured resume features, highlighting the value of automated preprocessing in high-volume recruitment environments."),
        p("Content-based and collaborative filtering approaches have been applied to job recommendation with moderate success. Hybrid recommendation systems that combine both paradigms — leveraging job description semantics and historical application behavior — consistently outperform single-method approaches in hit rate and user satisfaction metrics (Wilson, 2023)."),
        p("The integration of Large Language Models (LLMs) in recruitment tooling represents the current frontier. GPT-4 class models have been shown to perform competitively in structured information extraction from unstructured resume text, including skill identification, experience quantification, and education parsing — tasks previously requiring specialized NLP pipelines (Ahmed, 2022)."),

        h2("2.3 Explainable AI in HR Systems"),
        p("The growing adoption of AI in high-stakes decision-making contexts — including hiring — has generated substantial research interest in Explainable AI (XAI). The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) Article 22 specifically grants individuals the right to receive an explanation for automated decisions that significantly affect them, creating both an ethical and legal imperative for XAI in recruitment."),
        p("Counterfactual explanations have emerged as one of the most practically useful XAI techniques in this domain. A counterfactual explanation answers the question: 'What would need to change for a different outcome to occur?' In the context of recruitment, this translates to statements such as 'Your match score of 68% would increase to 85% if you acquired a certification in Docker and two years of cloud infrastructure experience.' This approach, unlike feature attribution methods such as SHAP or LIME, provides directly actionable guidance rather than statistical attribution (Wilson, 2023)."),
        p("Despite its practical value, counterfactual XAI remains underimplemented in commercial recruitment platforms. HireAI addresses this gap directly through its XAI Engine, which generates counterfactual explanations as a first-class feature rather than an afterthought."),

        h2("2.4 Fairness and Bias in Machine Learning"),
        p("Algorithmic bias in hiring systems has received prominent attention following high-profile failures, most notably Amazon's internal AI recruiting tool which exhibited gender bias by systematically downranking resumes that included the word 'women' (Dastin, 2018). This case underscored the risk of training machine learning models on historically biased hiring data, which encodes and amplifies existing discrimination."),
        p("The field of Fairness-Aware Machine Learning has developed multiple quantitative metrics for measuring bias, including Demographic Parity, Equal Opportunity, and the Four-Fifths (80%) Rule — the last of which is codified in US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission guidelines as a test for adverse impact in employment selection. A system passes the Four-Fifths Rule when the selection rate for any protected group is at least 80% of the selection rate for the most favored group."),
        p("IBM's AI Fairness 360 (AIF360) toolkit and Microsoft's FairLearn library provide open-source implementations of bias detection and mitigation algorithms. Mitigation strategies include pre-processing (re-sampling training data), in-processing (modifying learning objectives), and post-processing (adjusting model outputs). HireAI implements post-processing Fairness-Aware Ranking at the candidate list level, ensuring that diversity is actively promoted in shortlisted candidate sets without modifying the underlying model."),

        h2("2.5 NLP-Based Resume Parsing"),
        p("Resume parsing — the automated extraction of structured information from unstructured resume documents — is a foundational capability for intelligent recruitment systems. Early approaches relied on rule-based systems and template matching, which proved brittle across the diverse formats, fonts, and structures of real-world resumes."),
        p("Named Entity Recognition (NER) models, particularly those built on transformer architectures (BERT, RoBERTa), have significantly improved the accuracy of skill, education, and experience extraction. Garg et al. (2020) demonstrated that NLP-powered systems could extract candidate attributes with accuracy exceeding 90% on structured resumes, dropping to approximately 75% on highly unstructured or creatively formatted documents."),
        p("Applicant Tracking Systems (ATS) are used by the majority of large enterprises to pre-screen resumes before human review. ATS systems score resumes against job descriptions based on keyword presence, formatting compliance, and section completeness. A significant challenge for job seekers is ATS opacity — they are rarely told how their resume was scored or what improvements would increase their ranking. HireAI's Resume Analyzer addresses this directly by surfacing the scoring rationale and providing specific, actionable improvement suggestions."),
        p("Cosine similarity on TF-IDF vectors and embedding-based similarity using sentence transformers (e.g., all-MiniLM-L6-v2 from HuggingFace) are the dominant techniques for semantic matching between resume content and job descriptions. Embedding-based approaches significantly outperform TF-IDF on vocabulary mismatch cases, as they capture semantic relationships in continuous vector space rather than surface lexical overlap."),

        h2("2.6 Research Gap"),
        p("A comprehensive review of the literature reveals a significant gap: while individual components of intelligent recruitment (resume parsing, recommendation engines, fairness-aware algorithms, XAI) have been researched in isolation, no single platform integrates all of these capabilities into a production-ready, user-facing application. Commercial platforms prioritize scale and user base growth over AI sophistication, while academic research typically produces proof-of-concept implementations not designed for real-world deployment."),
        p("HireAI is designed to bridge this gap by implementing research-grade AI modules — including semantic skill matching via ESCO taxonomy, counterfactual XAI, and AIF360-based fairness ranking — within a fully functional, deployable web application serving real user needs in the Pakistani and broader job market context."),

        pageBreak(),

        // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        // CHAPTER 3: SYSTEM DESIGN & ARCHITECTURE
        // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        h1("Chapter 3: System Design and Architecture"),

        h2("3.1 System Overview"),
        p("HireAI is designed as a distributed, microservices-inspired web application. The system is partitioned into three primary layers: a React.js-based frontend Single Page Application (SPA), a Node.js/Express.js RESTful API backend, and a Python/FastAPI AI microservice responsible for all machine learning inference. This separation of concerns allows each layer to be independently scaled, updated, and tested, while also enabling the Python AI service to leverage the mature Python ML ecosystem independently of the JavaScript backend."),
        p("The system supports three primary user roles — Job Seeker, Employer, and Administrator — each with distinct access privileges enforced through Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) implemented via JWT-based authentication. A fourth state, Guest, represents unauthenticated users who may browse public job listings and company profiles without registration."),

        h2("3.2 High-Level Architecture"),
        p("The HireAI architecture follows a client-server model with an additional AI processing tier. User requests originate from the React frontend and are routed through the Node.js API Gateway, which handles authentication, request validation, and orchestration. AI-intensive operations — resume parsing, match scoring, XAI explanation generation, fairness re-ranking — are delegated via HTTP to the Python FastAPI microservice. External job data is aggregated through the JSearch API (a RapidAPI service that unifies LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor data) via a backend proxy to prevent CORS violations and protect API key credentials."),

        makeTable(
          ["Layer", "Technology", "Responsibility"],
          [
            ["Frontend", "React.js + Vite + Redux Toolkit", "User interface, state management, role-based routing"],
            ["API Gateway", "Node.js + Express.js", "Authentication, request routing, business logic, DB access"],
            ["AI Microservice", "Python + FastAPI", "Resume parsing, ATS scoring, XAI, fairness ranking, chatbot"],
            ["Database", "MongoDB Atlas", "User profiles, jobs, applications, session data"],
            ["File Storage", "Cloudinary", "Resume and profile image storage"],
            ["External APIs", "JSearch (RapidAPI)", "Real-time job aggregation from LinkedIn/Indeed/Glassdoor"],
          ],
          [2200, 2800, 4360]
        ),

        ...spacer(1),

        h2("3.3 Frontend Architecture"),
        p("The frontend is built with React.js 18 using Vite as the build tool, providing near-instant hot module replacement during development and optimized production bundles. The component architecture is organized into domain-specific modules: authentication, job discovery, profile management, employer dashboard, admin panel, and AI feature panels."),
        p("State management is handled by Redux Toolkit, with separate slices for authentication state, job listings, application tracking, company data, and UI state. Redux Persist ensures that user session data and preferences survive page refreshes. React Router v6 handles client-side routing with protected route components that enforce role-based access, redirecting unauthorized users to appropriate landing pages."),
        p("The UI component library is shadcn/ui, built on Radix UI primitives, ensuring accessible, keyboard-navigable, and screen-reader-compatible interfaces. Framer Motion is used for page transitions and micro-animations that enhance perceived performance. Tailwind CSS provides the utility-first styling system with a custom design token configuration aligned with HireAI's visual identity."),

        h2("3.4 Backend Architecture"),
        p("The backend API is built with Node.js and Express.js, organized in a layered MVC (Model-View-Controller) pattern with clear separation between route definitions, controller logic, middleware, and data access. The Express application serves as an API Gateway, handling JWT verification middleware on protected routes, Multer-based file upload processing for resume ingestion, and cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) configuration."),
        p("MongoDB is used as the primary database with Mongoose as the ODM layer for schema definition and validation. MongoDB's flexible document model is well-suited to the diverse and nested data structures inherent in recruitment data, including resume content, skill arrays, application histories, and embedded company profiles. MongoDB Atlas provides managed hosting with automatic backups, global replication, and built-in monitoring."),

        h2("3.5 AI Microservice Architecture"),
        p("The Python AI microservice is built with FastAPI, chosen for its native asynchronous support, automatic OpenAPI documentation generation, and excellent compatibility with the Python data science ecosystem. The microservice exposes the following primary endpoints:"),
        bullet("/parse-resume — Accepts a PDF/DOCX file, returns structured JSON with extracted skills, experience, education, and an ATS score with improvement suggestions."),
        bullet("/match-score — Accepts a resume JSON object and a job description, returns a semantic match score using ESCO-enriched skill embeddings, plus a counterfactual explanation."),
        bullet("/rerank-candidates — Accepts a ranked candidate list, returns a fairness-reranked list with demographic parity annotations."),
        bullet("/chatbot — Accepts a conversation history and user message, returns an AI-generated career guidance response."),
        bullet("/analyze-job-post — Accepts a job description text, returns bias detection results and flagged gender-coded language."),

        h2("3.6 Database Design"),
        p("The MongoDB schema is organized around five primary collections: Users, Jobs, Companies, Applications, and Sessions. The Users collection stores profile data differentiated by role, with embedded sub-documents for resume data, skill arrays, and application history references. The Jobs collection stores both internally posted jobs and metadata records for externally aggregated jobs, with a source field distinguishing internal versus JSearch-origin records. The Applications collection maintains the full application lifecycle, including status transitions (Applied, Reviewed, Shortlisted, Rejected) with timestamps for analytics."),

        makeTable(
          ["Collection", "Key Fields", "Notes"],
          [
            ["Users", "role, profile, skills[], resumeUrl, atsScore", "Polymorphic: job seeker vs employer fields"],
            ["Jobs", "title, description, skills[], source, companyId", "source: 'internal' | 'jsearch'"],
            ["Companies", "name, logoUrl, openPositions, industry", "Referenced by Jobs and Users"],
            ["Applications", "userId, jobId, status, matchScore, xaiExplanation", "Full audit trail with timestamps"],
            ["Sessions", "userId, token, expiresAt", "JWT blacklist for secure logout"],
          ],
          [1800, 3100, 4460]
        ),

        ...spacer(1),

        h2("3.7 External Integrations"),
        p("HireAI integrates with several external services. The JSearch API (via RapidAPI) provides access to normalized job listings aggregated from LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor. The backend acts as a proxy for JSearch requests, normalizing the response schema to HireAI's internal job format through a transformer function that maps external field names (e.g., job_title) to internal conventions (e.g., title). LinkedIn OAuth 2.0 is integrated for single-sign-on login and optional profile data import. Google OAuth is also supported. Cloudinary provides cloud-based storage and delivery for uploaded resumes and company logos, with automatic format conversion and CDN-based delivery."),

