        h1("1. INTRODUCTION"),

        h2("1.1 Introduction"),

        p("The rapid digitalization of global labor markets has fundamentally transformed recruitment workflows. Traditional job portals—dominant platforms such as LinkedIn, Indeed, Monster, and regional services like Rozee.pk—have become the primary intermediaries connecting employers and job seekers. However, despite widespread adoption, these platforms operate on fundamentally limited paradigms rooted in lexical keyword matching, offering minimal semantic understanding of candidate profiles, providing no personalized career guidance, and delivering zero feedback mechanisms for unsuccessful applicants."),

        p("Research indicates that keyword-based matching systems produce high rates of false negatives where genuinely qualified candidates are filtered out due to terminological differences. A candidate listing 'TensorFlow' may not match a job requiring 'Machine Learning' despite clear conceptual overlap. Similarly, recruiters face overwhelming application volumes with little automated intelligence to assist in objective, fair, and efficient shortlisting processes. The absence of explainability in AI-assisted hiring systems has drawn growing scrutiny from ethicists, regulators, and applicants who deserve transparent insight into automated decisions affecting their livelihoods."),

        p("HireAI was conceived and developed as a Final Year Project at Bahria University, Karachi Campus, to systematically address these structural deficiencies in contemporary recruitment technology. The platform reframes recruitment as a semantic understanding and fairness-enforcement problem rather than a surface-level keyword matching exercise, introducing decision transparency through counterfactual explanations and enforcing demographic equity through algorithmic fairness safeguards."),

        h2("1.2 Problem Statement"),

        p("Current job portal systems fail to provide intelligent, personalized, and equitable experiences for both job seekers and employers across multiple critical dimensions:"),

        bullet("Vocabulary Mismatch: Keyword-based matching systems fail when candidates use synonymous or contextually equivalent terminology for skills and experience, leading to false negatives in candidate discovery despite actual qualification."),
        bullet("Algorithmic Bias: Automated candidate ranking systems, where they exist, lack fairness-aware mechanisms and bias detection capabilities, potentially perpetuating historical biases in hiring based on gender, geographic location, or demographic characteristics."),
        bullet("Black Box Rejection: AI systems that score or rank candidates provide no explanation to unsuccessful applicants, creating an opaque and demotivating experience while preventing candidates from understanding improvement pathways."),
        bullet("Manual Screening Inefficiency: Employers continue to invest disproportionate time in manual resume review, with no intelligent pre-screening infrastructure that accounts for holistic candidate fit beyond keyword presence."),
        bullet("Platform Fragmentation: Job seekers must maintain separate profiles across multiple disconnected platforms (LinkedIn, Indeed, Rozee.pk, Glassdoor) without unified interfaces aggregating the broader job market landscape."),
        bullet("Absence of Career Intelligence: Existing platforms provide no skill gap analysis, personalized learning path recommendations, or structured interview preparation support."),

        h2("1.3 Background / Literature Review"),

        p("The application of artificial intelligence to recruitment has been an active area of research and industry development. Early approaches focused on automating resume parsing using rule-based systems and regular expressions, evolving into machine learning-based screening systems. Research by Li and Zhao (2021) demonstrated that ML-based resume screening could reduce hiring time by up to 50% while improving candidate quality metrics. Hybrid recommendation systems combining content-based and collaborative filtering have been shown to outperform single-method approaches in hit rate and user satisfaction."),

        p("The integration of Large Language Models in recruitment tooling represents the current frontier, with transformer-based models demonstrating competitive performance in structured information extraction from unstructured resume text. However, the organizational implications of AI in hiring have generated substantial ethical and legal scrutiny. The European Union's GDPR Article 22 specifically grants individuals the right to receive explanations for automated decisions significantly affecting them, creating legal imperatives for Explainable AI in recruitment contexts."),

        p("Counterfactual explanations have emerged as particularly valuable XAI techniques, answering 'What would need to change for a different outcome?' rather than merely attributing statistical importance to features. Despite this, counterfactual XAI remains critically underimplemented in commercial recruitment platforms."),

        p("Algorithmic bias in hiring systems received prominent attention following Amazon's internal AI recruiting tool exhibiting systematic gender bias. This catalyzed the development of Fairness-Aware Machine Learning with quantitative metrics including Demographic Parity, Equal Opportunity, and the Four-Fifths Rule codified in US EEOC guidelines. IBM's AI Fairness 360 toolkit and Microsoft's FairLearn library provide open-source implementations of bias detection and mitigation algorithms through pre-processing, in-processing, and post-processing strategies."),

        h2("1.4 Problem in existing system"),

        p("Analysis of dominant job portal platforms reveals systematic deficiencies:"),

        bullet("LinkedIn: Despite extensive professional networking capabilities and rich profile data, offers no ATS-style scoring, career coaching, or counterfactual feedback for unsuccessful applications. Skill endorsement system is self-reported and unverified."),
        bullet("Indeed: Operates primarily as a job aggregator with basic keyword filtering and simple apply mechanisms, offering minimal matching intelligence."),
        bullet("Rozee.pk: Functions similarly to early-generation job boards with keyword search, category filters, and predominantly manual recruiter workflows."),
        bullet("Common Weakness: All platforms rely on lexical (keyword-based) rather than semantic (meaning-based) matching, producing high false-negative rates and providing zero transparency when automated filtering occurs."),

        h2("1.5 Proposed Solution"),

        p("HireAI addresses these systemic failures through a comprehensive platform integrating four core AI modules within a production-ready full-stack web application. The solution reframes recruitment as a semantic understanding problem augmented with fairness enforcement and decision transparency."),

        h3("1.5.1 Features of the project"),

