      }),
      body("Semantic matching represents skills as nodes in a graph where edges encode ontological relationships [9]. For a job description J and resume R, semantic similarity is computed as:"),
      equation("Sim(J, R) = Σ max_{r ∈ R} graph_distance(j, r) / |J|"),
      body("where graph_distance(j, r) denotes the shortest path between skill nodes j and r in the ESCO Knowledge Graph. Skills within a predefined path threshold θ are considered matches, enabling context-aware resolution of vocabulary differences."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"3.2 Natural Language Processing for Resume Parsing",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("SpaCy's NER pipeline, combined with custom skill entity models trained on ESCO-labeled data, forms the backbone of HireAI's CV Analysis Engine. The ATS score is computed as a weighted combination of skill match ratio, experience relevance, and education alignment:"),
      equation("ATS_Score = w₁ × SkillMatch + w₂ × ExperienceScore + w₃ × EducationScore"),
      body("where the weights w₁, w₂, w₃ are configurable per job posting category and sum to 1.0."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"3.3 Fairness-Aware Machine Learning",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("HireAI adopts the Demographic Parity criterion, measured by the Demographic Parity Ratio (DPR):"),
      equation("DPR = P(Ŷ = 1 | A = minority) / P(Ŷ = 1 | A = majority)"),
      body("where Ŷ is the binary shortlist outcome and A is the sensitive demographic attribute. A DPR ≥ 0.8 satisfies the Four-Fifths Rule [12]. FairLearn's post-processing re-ranking algorithm adjusts the shortlist to achieve this target."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"3.4 Counterfactual Explanations",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("A counterfactual explanation for a rejected candidate is a minimal perturbation to their profile that would change the model's decision from rejection to acceptance [5]. Given a candidate feature vector x and f(x) = 0 (rejected), the counterfactual x' is:"),
      equation("x' = argmin ||x' - x|| such that f(x') = 1"),
      body("In HireAI's XAI Engine, the feature space consists of discrete skill entities, certifications, and experience levels, making the search tractable through a greedy skill-gap enumeration algorithm. The resulting counterfactual is rendered as natural language using GPT-4o-mini."),

      ...spacer(1),

      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      // SECTION 4 – DATASETS
      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"4. System Data Sources",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"4.1 Internal MongoDB Database",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The internal database stores platform-native entities across three primary collections. The **Users** collection captures profiles for job seekers (skills, experience, education, uploaded resume metadata) and employers (company profile, posted jobs, hiring preferences). The **Jobs** collection stores employer-created job postings with structured fields including required skills, salary range, location, and employment type. The **Applications** collection tracks the lifecycle of each application from submission through to shortlist decision, storing ATS scores, XAI explanation text, and final status. Data quality is maintained through schema validation enforced by Mongoose ODM."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"4.2 Real-Time External Job Market Data (JSearch API)",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("To solve the cold-start problem inherent to newly launched platforms, HireAI integrates the JSearch API (via RapidAPI), which aggregates real-time job listings from LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor. A backend Transformer Function normalizes heterogeneous vendor-specific JSON into HireAI's canonical Job schema before delivery to the frontend. The normalization mapping is presented in Table 2."),
      caption("Table 2. Data normalization mapping between JSearch API fields and HireAI canonical schema."),
      makeTable2(),

      ...spacer(1),
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"4.3 Relevance Between Internal and External Data Sources",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("Both data sources share the common purpose of populating HireAI's job discovery layer. Table 3 summarizes feature parity between the two sources, enabling seamless toggling between Internal Database Mode and Live Market Mode."),
      caption("Table 3. Relevance between internal database jobs and JSearch API external jobs. (✓) Yes."),
      makeTable3(),

      ...spacer(1),

      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      // SECTION 5 – METHODOLOGY
      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5. Proposed HireAI Architecture and Methodology",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5.1 System Architecture Overview",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("HireAI follows a microservices-inspired architecture comprising four layers. The **Frontend** is built with React.js and Vite, using Redux Toolkit for global state management and shadcn/ui for component design. Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) differentiates three user roles: Guest, Job Seeker, and Employer, dynamically rendering different navigation structures and dashboard layouts per role. The **Backend API Gateway** is implemented in Node.js with Express.js, providing RESTful endpoints and acting as a reverse proxy for all external API calls, resolving browser-level CORS restrictions while protecting API keys. The **AI Microservice Layer** is implemented as a Python FastAPI service, enabling independent scaling of AI-intensive operations. The **Data Layer** uses MongoDB Atlas for document storage and Cloudinary for resume and media file management."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5.2 Module A: Semantic Intelligence Engine",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The Semantic Intelligence Engine addresses the vocabulary mismatch problem through a four-step pipeline. In **Step 1 (Document Parsing)**, the uploaded PDF is converted to raw text using PyMuPDF, and SpaCy's NER pipeline extracts all skill mentions. In **Step 2 (Skill Graph Mapping)**, each skill is looked up in the ESCO Knowledge Graph; if no exact match is found, a fuzzy string matching algorithm (Levenshtein distance ≤ 2) identifies the closest node within the same skill cluster. In **Step 3 (Semantic Matching)**, the match score is computed as the proportion of required job skills for which the candidate has an exact or semantically equivalent match. In **Step 4 (ATS Score Generation)**, the final ATS score combines the semantic skill match ratio with normalized experience relevance and education alignment scores per the formula in Section 3.2."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5.3 Module B: Fairness-Aware Ranking",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The FAR Module is applied as a post-processing step after the initial ATS-based candidate ranking. It operates in two sub-components. The **Bias Audit Dashboard** analyzes employer job descriptions for gender-coded language using a lexicon derived from prior work [13], highlighting masculine-coded or feminine-coded words with suggested neutral alternatives before posting. The **Candidate Re-Ranking** sub-component applies FairLearn's post-processing algorithm to re-rank applicant shortlists to satisfy DPR ≥ 0.8. Candidate demographic attributes are used solely for fairness auditing and are never surfaced to employers in the primary application view, implementing anonymous shortlisting as a second layer of bias protection."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5.4 Module C: Explainable AI Engine",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The XAI Engine generates two forms of explanation for each candidate-job interaction. **Contribution Charts** provide a visual breakdown of the ATS score showing the contribution of each component (skill match, experience, education) rendered as a bar chart on the candidate's dashboard. **Counterfactual Explanations** compute the minimal skill gap that would bring the match score above the employer's shortlist threshold, then pass this to GPT-4o-mini to render as a friendly, actionable natural language message — for example: \"You scored 68% for this role. Adding a certification in Docker would increase your score by approximately 7%.\""),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5.5 Module D: Hybrid Job Discovery Engine",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The Hybrid Job Discovery Engine provides users with two simultaneously available job pools. **Internal Mode** queries the MongoDB Jobs collection and supports custom filters including salary range in PKR, job type, and location, with results pre-scored against the user's profile via the ATS engine. **External Mode (Live Market)** proxies the query to the JSearch API via the backend, normalizes the response through the Transformer Function, and returns results in the same card format as internal listings. The toggle between modes is seamless, with Skeleton Loader animations managing asynchronous latency."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"5.6 Performance Evaluation Parameters",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The system is evaluated against five metrics: (1) **ATS Parsing Accuracy** — proportion of synonymous skill mentions correctly resolved to their ESCO equivalent, on a held-out set of 200 annotated resumes; (2) **Semantic Match Recall** — proportion of genuinely relevant jobs surfaced in the top-10 recommendations; (3) **Demographic Parity Ratio (DPR)** — computed per job posting after FAR re-ranking, target DPR ≥ 0.8; (4) **Explanation Fidelity** — degree to which counterfactual explanations accurately reflect the underlying model's decision boundary, measured using LIME fidelity scores; (5) **System Performance** — API response time, memory consumption, and concurrent user capacity."),

      ...spacer(1),

      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      // SECTION 6 – RESULTS
      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"6. Experiments and Results",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"6.1 Experimental Setup",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("All experiments are performed on the development environment summarized in Table 4. The evaluation is conducted in three phases: Phase I assesses the Semantic Intelligence Engine's parsing accuracy; Phase II evaluates the FAR module's fairness outcomes; Phase III assesses overall system usability and performance under load."),
      caption("Table 4. Summary of experimental setup."),
      makeTable4(),

      ...spacer(1),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"6.2 Semantic Intelligence Engine Evaluation",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The skill extraction pipeline was evaluated on a held-out test set of 200 resumes spanning five job categories. Human annotators labeled all skill mentions with their canonical ESCO identifiers, providing ground truth. Table 5 presents precision, recall, and F1 scores for skill extraction and semantic matching."),
      caption("Table 5. Semantic skill extraction and matching performance by job category."),
      makeTable5(),
      ...spacer(1),
      body("Overall semantic match accuracy of 84.7% approaches the 85% target, with Software Engineering (87.3%) and DevOps (86.2%) exceeding it. Product Management, which involves the most abstract vocabulary, performs slightly below target, indicating that further ESCO taxonomy coverage for business and strategy skills would improve performance in this domain."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"6.3 Fairness-Aware Ranking Evaluation",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The FAR module was evaluated using a synthetic candidate dataset of 500 records with balanced gender representation across three job categories. Table 6 presents Demographic Parity Ratios before and after FAR re-ranking."),
      caption("Table 6. Demographic Parity Ratio before and after Fairness-Aware Re-ranking."),
      makeTable6(),
      ...spacer(1),
      body("Results confirm that the initial ATS-based ranking produces DPR values below 0.8 across all categories — consistent with literature findings [12] — while FAR re-ranking restores demographic parity above 0.8 in all cases. The average post-FAR DPR of 0.85 satisfies the project's fairness success criterion."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"6.4 System Performance Evaluation",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("Table 7 presents key performance metrics measured during load testing."),
      caption("Table 7. System performance metrics under load testing conditions."),
      makeTable7(),
      ...spacer(1),
      body("Standard API responses are well within the 2-second target. The system successfully handled over 12,000 concurrent users in stress testing — exceeding the project's scalability target. AI analysis queries require approximately 3.2 seconds, which is acceptable for a non-real-time operation and mitigated in the UI by asynchronous progress indicators."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_2, spacing:{before:200,after:80},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"6.5 Qualitative Results: Explainability",bold:true,size:22,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("A user study was conducted with 30 participants (15 job seekers, 15 recent graduates) who were shown rejection notifications with and without counterfactual explanations and rated them on three Likert-scale dimensions (1–5). Table 8 presents the results."),
      caption("Table 8. User study results for XAI counterfactual explanations (n=30, Likert scale 1–5)."),
      makeTable8(),
      ...spacer(1),
      body("Counterfactual explanations dramatically improved all three user experience dimensions, with actionability showing the largest improvement (+221.4%). Qualitative feedback highlighted that participants particularly valued knowing the specific skill gap and the quantified score impact, allowing targeted upskilling decisions."),

      ...spacer(1),

      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      // SECTION 7 – CONCLUSIONS
      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"7. Conclusions",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("This paper presented HireAI, an AI-enhanced intelligent job portal that addresses three critical failures of traditional recruitment platforms: vocabulary mismatch, algorithmic bias, and lack of explainability. The proposed system integrates a Semantic Intelligence Engine based on ESCO skill ontologies, a Fairness-Aware Ranking module compliant with the Four-Fifths Rule, an Explainable AI Engine delivering actionable counterfactual explanations, and a Hybrid Job Discovery Engine unifying internal and real-time external job market data."),
      body("Experimental evaluation demonstrated semantic skill matching accuracy of 84.7% across five job categories. Fairness evaluation confirmed that the FAR module elevates Demographic Parity Ratios from 0.67 to 0.85 on average, satisfying the Four-Fifths Rule across all tested categories. System performance validated capacity for over 12,000 concurrent users with sub-850ms standard query response times. User study results confirmed that counterfactual explanations significantly improve candidate-perceived clarity, actionability, and trust compared to standard rejection notifications."),
      body("HireAI advances the state of practice in AI-driven recruitment by being, to the authors' knowledge, the first unified system to address semantic matching, fairness, and explainability simultaneously within a single deployable web platform."),
      body("Future directions include: (1) expanding ESCO Knowledge Graph coverage for non-technical domains to improve Product Management category performance; (2) adaptive re-training of the ranking model as platform-native hiring outcomes accumulate; (3) multi-class ATS scoring for multi-role career transitions; and (4) integrating video-based AI mock interview assessment modules for end-to-end candidate readiness evaluation."),

      ...spacer(1),

      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      // CREDIT + DECLARATIONS
      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"CRediT Authorship Contribution Statement",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("**M. Saud Al Faisal:** Writing – original draft, Frontend development, UX design, Data visualization, Project management, Conceptualization. **Syed Abdul Rafay:** Writing – review & editing, Backend architecture, API gateway development, Database schema design, External API integration. **Faisal Wahab:** Writing – review & editing, AI microservice development, Knowledge graph implementation, Fairness algorithm integration, Explainability engine development."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"Declaration of Competing Interest",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper."),

      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"Data Availability",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),
      body("The ESCO taxonomy data used for skill graph construction is publicly available at https://esco.ec.europa.eu. Source code is available from the corresponding author upon reasonable request."),

      ...spacer(1),

      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      // REFERENCES
      // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
      new Paragraph({ heading: HeadingLevel.HEADING_1, spacing:{before:280,after:120},
        children:[new TextRun({text:"References",bold:true,size:28,font:"Arial",color:BLUE})]
      }),

      ...[
        "[1] M. Nikolaou, \"AI in Recruitment: The Future of Hiring,\" IEEE Transactions on Engineering Management, vol. 68, no. 4, pp. 1102–1114, 2021.",
        "[2] S. Ahmed, \"Artificial Intelligence in Recruitment and Selection: A Review,\" Springer Applied Intelligence, vol. 51, pp. 879–895, 2022.",
        "[3] B. Li and J. Zhao, \"Automated Resume Screening with Machine Learning,\" Journal of Intelligent Information Systems, vol. 56, pp. 223–239, 2021.",
        "[4] A. Köchling and M. C. Wehner, \"Discriminated by an Algorithm: A Systematic Review of Discrimination and Fairness by Algorithmic Decision-Making in the Context of HR Recruitment,\" Business Research, vol. 13, no. 3, pp. 795–848, 2020.",
        "[5] S. Wachter, B. Mittelstadt, and C. Russell, \"Counterfactual Explanations Without Opening the Black Box: Automated Decisions and the GDPR,\" Harvard Journal of Law and Technology, vol. 31, no. 2, pp. 841–887, 2018.",
        "[6] D. Wilson, \"The Role of AI in Career Guidance and Job Matching,\" International Journal of Computer Applications, vol. 175, no. 6, 2023.",
        "[7] A. Bharadwaj and S. Bhattacharyya, \"Deep Learning-Based Skill Extraction from Resumes Using Bidirectional LSTM Networks,\" Expert Systems with Applications, vol. 198, p. 116842, 2022.",
        "[8] B. Li, J. Zhang, and Y. Wang, \"BERT-Based Job-Resume Matching: A Transformer Approach to Intelligent Recruitment,\" Journal of Intelligent Information Systems, vol. 59, no. 2, pp. 441–460, 2022.",
        "[9] S. Fareri, L. Fantoni, F. Chiarello, E. Coli, and A. Quarta, \"Estimating Industry 4.0 Impact on Job Profiles and Skills Using Text Mining,\" Computers in Industry, vol. 118, p. 103222, 2020.",
        "[10] Y. Zhang, H. Chen, and W. Li, \"A Hybrid Collaborative-Content Filtering Approach for Job Recommendation Using Real-Time Market Data,\" Future Generation Computer Systems, vol. 148, pp. 213–227, 2023.",
        "[11] J. Dastin, \"Amazon Scraps Secret AI Recruiting Tool that Showed Bias Against Women,\" Reuters Technology News, 2018.",
        "[12] M. Raghavan, S. Barocas, J. Kleinberg, and K. Levy, \"Mitigating Bias in Algorithmic Hiring: Evaluating Claims and Practices,\" in Proc. ACM FAccT, 2020, pp. 469–481.",
        "[13] D. Gaucher, J. Friesen, and A. C. Kay, \"Evidence that Gendered Wording in Job Advertisements Exists and Sustains Gender Inequality,\" Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, vol. 101, no. 1, pp. 109–128, 2011.",
        "[14] M. Bogen and A. Rieke, \"Help Wanted: An Examination of Hiring Algorithms, Equity, and Bias,\" Upturn Policy Report, 2018.",
        "[15] B. Piacentino, C. Triguero, and A. García, \"Explainable AI for Resume Screening: Applying LIME to Graduate Hiring Models,\" Applied Soft Computing, vol. 128, p. 109421, 2022.",
        "[16] A. Garg, T. Morales, and R. Patel, \"Natural Language Processing Applications in Human Resources: A Systematic Review,\" Artificial Intelligence Review, vol. 53, pp. 3323–3356, 2020.",
        "[17] X. Qin, Y. Zhu, and J. Chen, \"A Multi-View Learning Framework for Intelligent Job Recommendation in Online Recruitment Platforms,\" IEEE Transactions on Knowledge and Data Engineering, vol. 35, no. 4, pp. 3421–3434, 2023.",
        "[18] P. Sánchez, A. H. Celdrán, G. Bovet, and G. M. Pérez, \"Adversarial Attacks and Defenses on ML-Based IoT Device Identification,\" Future Generation Computer Systems, vol. 152, pp. 30–42, 2024.",
      ].map(ref => new Paragraph({
        alignment: AlignmentType.JUSTIFIED,
        spacing: { after: 80 },
        indent: { left: 360, hanging: 360 },
        children: [new TextRun({ text: ref, size: 18, font: "Arial", color: "333333" })]
      })),

    ] // end children
  }] // end sections
});

Packer.toBuffer(doc).then(buffer => {
