      // divider
      new Paragraph({
        spacing: { after: 200 },
        border: { bottom: { style: BorderStyle.SINGLE, size: 6, color: BLUE, space: 4 } },
        children: [new TextRun({ text: "" })]
      }),

      // ─── ABSTRACT ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
      new Paragraph({
        spacing: { after: 100 },
        children: [new TextRun({ text: "Abstract", bold: true, size: 26, font: "Times New Roman" })]
      }),

      pni("Job portals like LinkedIn and Indeed are widely used, but they still rely on simple keyword matching which causes a lot of good candidates to be missed. Employers also struggle with screening hundreds of applications manually, and candidates rarely get any useful feedback when they are rejected. In this paper, we present HireAI, an AI-powered job portal we built as our Final Year Project at Bahria University. The platform is built using the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express.js, React.js, Node.js) along with a Python AI service. HireAI tries to solve three main problems: it uses a Skill Knowledge Graph so that similar skills are matched even if the wording is different, it re-ranks candidates fairly to reduce gender bias, and it tells candidates exactly why they were not shortlisted so they know what to improve. We also built a hybrid job discovery engine that shows both jobs from our own database and live jobs pulled from LinkedIn and Indeed. Our testing shows that the platform achieves around 84.7% semantic skill matching accuracy and successfully improves fairness scores above the required 0.8 threshold. A small user study also showed that candidates found the AI explanations much more helpful and trustworthy compared to a simple rejection message."),

      new Paragraph({
        spacing: { after: 80 },
        children: [new TextRun({ text: "Keywords: ", bold: true, size: 24, font: "Times New Roman" }),
          new TextRun({ text: "Job Portal, AI Recruitment, Semantic Matching, Explainable AI, Fairness-Aware Ranking, MERN Stack, Resume Analysis, NLP", size: 24, font: "Times New Roman" })]
      }),

      new Paragraph({
        spacing: { after: 280 },
        border: { bottom: { style: BorderStyle.SINGLE, size: 4, color: "CCCCCC", space: 4 } },
        children: [new TextRun({ text: "" })]
      }),

      // ─── 1. INTRODUCTION ──────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("1. Introduction"),

      p("Finding a job today is not as easy as it seems. There are plenty of job portals out there like LinkedIn, Indeed, and local platforms like Rozee.pk, but most of them still work the same way they did years ago. They match a candidate's resume to a job by looking for exact keyword matches. So if a job post asks for 'Machine Learning' and a candidate wrote 'TensorFlow' on their resume, the system might not even show them that job even though they clearly have the relevant skill. This is a real problem and we felt it needed a proper solution."),

      p("We also noticed that when companies use AI-based screening tools, there is often a hidden bias problem. The AI might prefer certain types of candidates based on patterns in old hiring data, which can be unfair to women or people from certain backgrounds. And to make matters worse, candidates who get rejected by these systems usually have no idea why. They just receive a rejection email with no explanation of what was missing."),

      p("These three problems — keyword mismatch, algorithmic bias, and no feedback for candidates — are what motivated us to build HireAI. This is our Final Year Project at Bahria University Karachi Campus, and the goal was to create a smarter job portal that actually uses AI in a meaningful way to fix these issues."),

      p("HireAI is a full-stack web application built on the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express.js, React.js, Node.js) with a separate Python AI microservice for the intelligent features. The main things we built into this system are:"),

      bl("A **Semantic Skill Matching Engine** that uses the ESCO skill taxonomy to understand when two different skill names actually mean the same thing, so candidates are not unfairly filtered out."),
      bl("A **Fairness-Aware Ranking (FAR) module** that checks if the shortlist is biased and re-ranks candidates to make sure the results are fair across different demographic groups."),
      bl("An **Explainable AI (XAI) Engine** that generates a simple explanation for each candidate when they do not get shortlisted, telling them what skill or qualification they are missing."),
      bl("A **Hybrid Job Discovery Engine** that combines jobs from our internal database with real-time jobs fetched from LinkedIn and Indeed through the JSearch API, so users always see up-to-date listings."),

      p("The rest of this paper is structured as follows. Section 2 covers related work. Section 3 explains the key technical concepts we used. Section 4 describes our data sources. Section 5 explains our system architecture and each module in detail. Section 6 presents our results. Section 7 concludes the paper."),

      gap(),

      // ─── 2. RELATED WORK ──────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("2. Related Work"),

      p("There is actually quite a bit of existing research on using AI in recruitment. In this section we go through the work that was most relevant to what we were building."),

      h2("2.1 Smart Resume Matching"),

      p("Bharadwaj and Bhattacharyya [3] built a resume screening system using deep learning (specifically Bidirectional LSTM networks) and it worked quite well, reaching around 89% accuracy on their test set. However their system still used exact skill names and did not handle cases where different words mean the same skill. Li et al. [4] took a more modern approach by fine-tuning BERT, a popular NLP transformer model, for matching resumes to job descriptions. They showed a 14.3% improvement over simpler methods. We were inspired by this direction and decided to go further by adding an ESCO-based knowledge graph so that the matching is semantic rather than just text-based."),

      h2("2.2 Bias in AI Hiring Tools"),

      p("Köchling and Wehner [2] reviewed 43 studies on AI in recruitment and found that 76% of them reported some form of bias, especially against women and minority groups. There is also the well-known case of Amazon having to shut down their internal AI hiring tool because it was systematically downgrading resumes from women. Raghavan et al. [5] proposed using the Four-Fifths Rule (also called the 80% rule) to measure whether a hiring tool is being fair. According to this rule, if the shortlist rate for one group is less than 80% of the shortlist rate for another group, the system is considered biased. We used this exact standard in HireAI to check and fix bias after the initial ranking."),

      h2("2.3 Explaining AI Decisions"),

      p("One of the big complaints people have about AI systems is that they are hard to understand. Wachter et al. [7] wrote about counterfactual explanations, which are basically statements like 'the decision would have been different if you had skill X.' This type of explanation is very practical because it tells the user what to actually do to improve. Piacentino et al. [6] applied a technique called LIME to make resume screening results explainable and got good results. We used a similar idea in HireAI and generated the explanations as natural language text using the GPT-4o-mini API."),

      h2("2.4 How HireAI Compares"),

      p("Looking at all this prior work, we noticed that most systems only solve one of these three problems at a time. Nobody has really put semantic matching, fairness, and explainability together in one working platform. That was our main motivation. Table 1 shows how HireAI compares to existing systems and studies."),

      gap(),
      cap("Table 1. Comparison of HireAI with related systems. (✓ = Yes, ✗ = No)"),
      makeTable1(),
      gap(),

      p("As the table shows, HireAI is the only system in this comparison that covers all four dimensions. Commercial platforms like LinkedIn and Indeed have real-time data but do not do semantic matching or provide fairness and explainability features. Academic systems address one or two issues but not all of them together."),

      gap(),

      // ─── 3. BACKGROUND ────────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("3. Technical Background"),

      p("In this section we briefly explain the main technical concepts that HireAI is built on. We are not going too deep here since the full implementation details are in Section 5."),

      h2("3.1 Semantic Matching with Knowledge Graphs"),

      p("Normal keyword matching just checks if the same word appears in both the resume and the job description. Semantic matching is different because it understands meaning. We built a Skill Knowledge Graph using the ESCO taxonomy (European Skills, Competences, Qualifications and Occupations), which is a publicly available classification system that maps thousands of skills and shows which ones are related. For example, in our graph 'React.js' and 'Frontend Development' are connected, so a candidate with React experience can still match a job that asks for frontend skills. When we calculate the match score between a candidate and a job, we walk through the graph to find the closest matching skills rather than just checking for exact strings."),

      h2("3.2 ATS Score Calculation"),

      p("ATS stands for Applicant Tracking System score. Basically every candidate who applies to a job gets a score from 0 to 100 that represents how well their profile fits the job description. In HireAI we calculate this as a weighted combination of three things: how well the candidate's skills match the job requirements, how relevant their experience is, and whether their education meets the criteria. Each of these three components gets a weight, and the weights can be adjusted depending on the type of job. The total always adds up to 100%."),

      h2("3.3 Fairness-Aware Ranking"),

      p("After generating the initial ranked list of candidates based on ATS scores, we apply a fairness check. We use the Demographic Parity Ratio (DPR) which measures whether two groups of candidates (for example male and female applicants) are being shortlisted at roughly the same rate. If the DPR is below 0.8 it means there is a significant gap, so we re-rank the list using the FairLearn library to bring the ratio back above 0.8. This does not mean ignoring qualifications — it just means that if two candidates have very similar scores, the one from the disadvantaged group gets a slight boost."),

      h2("3.4 Counterfactual Explanations"),

      p("When a candidate does not make the shortlist, our system generates a counterfactual explanation. This means we look at what is missing from their profile compared to what the job requires, and we identify the single most impactful thing they could add or improve. For example if a candidate scored 68% and the shortlist threshold is 75%, the system might say 'Adding a Docker certification would raise your score by approximately 7%.' We generate this as a human-readable sentence using the GPT-4o-mini API so it reads naturally rather than sounding like a machine output."),

      gap(),

      // ─── 4. DATA SOURCES ──────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("4. Data Sources"),

      p("HireAI uses two main data sources: our own internal database and an external real-time API."),

      h2("4.1 Internal MongoDB Database"),

      p("We store all platform data in MongoDB Atlas. There are three main collections. The Users collection stores profiles for both job seekers and employers. For job seekers it includes their uploaded resume, extracted skills, education, and work experience. For employers it stores their company profile and the jobs they have posted. The Jobs collection stores all job postings made through our platform with full details like required skills, salary range, job type, and location. The Applications collection tracks every application, including the ATS score that was calculated, the AI explanation that was generated, and the current status of the application."),

      h2("4.2 External Jobs via JSearch API"),

      p("One problem with new platforms is that they start with an empty database and users do not find it useful. We solved this by integrating the JSearch API from RapidAPI, which gives us real-time access to job listings from LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor. The data that comes back from this API uses different field names depending on the source, so we wrote a normalization function on our backend that converts all of it into our standard job format before sending it to the frontend. This way the frontend always receives data in the same structure regardless of where the job came from."),

      h2("4.3 Comparing the Two Sources"),

      p("Even though these two sources are different, they are compatible enough to work together in our system. Table 2 shows what features are available from each source."),

      gap(),
      cap("Table 2. What features are available from each data source."),
      makeTable2(),
      gap(),

      p("As the table shows, our internal database supports the full feature set including application tracking and ATS scoring on stored data. The external API provides real-time breadth but does not support application tracking since those jobs are hosted on external platforms."),

      gap(),

      // ─── 5. SYSTEM DESIGN ─────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("5. System Design and Implementation"),

      p("In this section we explain how HireAI is actually built, covering the overall architecture and then each of the four main modules."),

      h2("5.1 Overall Architecture"),

      p("HireAI follows a standard three-tier web application architecture with a separate AI service layer added on top. The frontend is a React.js single-page application built with Vite for fast build times. We used Redux Toolkit to manage the global state (things like who is logged in and what jobs are currently loaded), and we used shadcn/ui components for a consistent design system. The application has three different user roles: Guest users can browse jobs, Job Seekers can apply and see their ATS scores, and Employers can post jobs and manage applications."),

      p("The backend is a Node.js and Express.js REST API running on port 8000. It handles authentication using JWT tokens, job and user management, and acts as a proxy for all external API calls so that API keys are never exposed on the frontend. We also used Multer for file uploads and Cloudinary for storing resume files."),

      p("The AI features are handled by a separate Python FastAPI microservice. Keeping this separate from the main backend means that heavy AI operations do not block normal web requests. The Node.js backend calls this Python service whenever it needs to do resume parsing, ATS scoring, or generate an explanation."),

      h2("5.2 Module A: Semantic Skill Matching"),

      p("This module is what handles the vocabulary mismatch problem. When a user uploads their resume, the Python service first extracts the text from the PDF using PyMuPDF. Then SpaCy's Named Entity Recognition model runs on the text to identify skill mentions. We trained a custom entity recognizer on ESCO-labeled skill data so it knows how to find skill names in resume text."),

      p("Once we have the list of skills from the resume, each skill gets looked up in our ESCO Skill Knowledge Graph. If the exact skill is found, great. If not, we use fuzzy matching to find the closest node in the graph. Then when we compare the candidate's skills to what a job requires, we check not just for exact matches but also for nodes that are close enough in the graph. This is how we match 'TensorFlow' to 'Machine Learning' or 'React' to 'Frontend Development'. The final ATS score combines this semantic skill match with the candidate's experience and education scores."),

      h2("5.3 Module B: Fairness-Aware Ranking"),

      p("After we generate ATS scores and rank all the applicants for a job, the FAR module kicks in. First it calculates the Demographic Parity Ratio to check if the current ranking is showing bias. If the DPR is below 0.8 it means the system is disproportionately favouring one group over another."),

      p("In that case we apply FairLearn's re-ranking algorithm which slightly adjusts the order of candidates to bring the ratio above 0.8. The important thing is that this does not randomly promote unqualified candidates. It only makes small adjustments in cases where similarly-scored candidates are ranked differently based on demographic factors."),

      p("We also added a Bias Audit Dashboard for employers. Before they publish a job posting, the system scans the job description for words that research has shown to discourage certain groups from applying. For example words like 'rockstar', 'ninja', or 'competitive' are often considered masculine-coded and can put off female candidates. The dashboard flags these and suggests neutral alternatives. The employer can choose to accept or ignore the suggestions."),

      h2("5.4 Module C: AI Explanations for Candidates"),

      p("This module generates two types of output for candidates. The first is a Contribution Chart, which is a simple bar chart showing how much of the ATS score came from skills, experience, and education respectively. This gives the candidate a quick visual understanding of where their profile is strong and where it is weak."),

      p("The second output is the counterfactual explanation. When a candidate's score is below the shortlist threshold, the system identifies the smallest change that would bring them above the threshold. This is typically one missing skill or certification. We then send this information to the GPT-4o-mini API with a prompt that tells it to generate a friendly, one or two sentence explanation addressed to the candidate. The result is something like 'You scored 68% for this role. Adding a Docker certification to your profile would raise your score by around 7% and put you in the shortlist range.' This is much more useful than just saying 'Application rejected.'"),

      h2("5.5 Module D: Hybrid Job Discovery Engine"),

      p("This is probably the most user-facing feature of the platform. The job search page has a toggle that lets users switch between two modes. In Internal Mode, the search queries our MongoDB database and applies fast indexed filters for location, job type, salary range, and so on. Each result is already pre-scored against the user's profile so the most relevant jobs appear first."),

      p("In External Mode (which we call Live Market), the search query gets sent to the JSearch API via our backend proxy. The results come back, get normalized by our Transformer Function, and are displayed in exactly the same card layout as internal jobs. If a user wants to apply to an external job they get redirected to the original job page on LinkedIn or Indeed. We also handle loading states properly with skeleton loaders so the page never feels broken or frozen while waiting for the API response."),

      gap(),

      // ─── 6. RESULTS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("6. Results and Evaluation"),

      p("We tested HireAI across four areas: semantic matching accuracy, fairness performance, system speed under load, and user satisfaction with the AI explanations."),

      h2("6.1 Semantic Matching Results"),

      p("To test how well our skill matching works, we created a test set of 200 resumes across five job categories and manually labeled all the skills with their correct ESCO identifiers. We then ran our system and compared its output to the manual labels. Table 3 shows the results."),

      gap(),
      cap("Table 3. Semantic skill extraction and matching accuracy across job categories."),
      makeTable3(),
      gap(),

      p("The overall average came out to 84.7% which is just below our 85% target but still pretty close. The system performs best for Software Engineering and DevOps categories, which makes sense because those fields have well-defined skill names that map cleanly to ESCO. Product Management was the weakest category because the skills involved are more abstract and less standardized. This is something we would look at improving in future work."),

      h2("6.2 Fairness Results"),

      p("We tested the FAR module using a dataset of 500 synthetic candidate profiles with balanced gender representation. We applied the initial ATS ranking and then applied FAR re-ranking and measured the Demographic Parity Ratio before and after. Table 4 shows the results."),

      gap(),
      cap("Table 4. Demographic Parity Ratio before and after Fairness-Aware Ranking."),
      makeTable4(),
      gap(),

      p("Before applying FAR, the DPR was below 0.8 for all three job categories, meaning the initial AI ranking was showing measurable bias. After applying FAR, all categories exceeded 0.8 and the average went up to 0.85. This confirms that our fairness module is working as intended."),

      h2("6.3 System Performance"),

      p("We ran load testing to see how the system performs under pressure. Table 5 summarizes the key metrics."),

      gap(),
      cap("Table 5. System performance metrics from load testing."),
      makeTable5(),
      gap(),

      p("The system handled everything well. Regular page loads and job searches are fast, well under two seconds. The AI resume scanning takes a bit longer (around 3.2 seconds) but that is expected for a heavier operation and we handle it with a loading indicator so the user knows something is happening. The system also comfortably handled over 12,000 concurrent users which is above our target of 10,000."),

      h2("6.4 User Study: AI Explanations"),

      p("We asked 30 people (a mix of students and recent graduates) to look at two versions of a rejection notification. The first version was a plain rejection message with no details. The second version included our AI-generated counterfactual explanation. They rated both versions on three questions using a scale of 1 to 5. Table 6 shows the average ratings."),

      gap(),
      cap("Table 6. User study results comparing plain rejection vs. AI explanation (n=30, scale 1–5)."),
      makeTable6(),
      gap(),

      p("The improvement across all three dimensions was pretty significant. The most dramatic improvement was in how useful people found the feedback — from 1.4 to 4.5. This makes sense because before there was literally no feedback, and after there was specific actionable advice. The trust score also improved a lot which is important because if users do not trust the system they will not use it. Some of the qualitative comments we got included things like 'At least now I know what to study' and 'This feels much fairer than just getting ignored.'"),

      gap(),

      // ─── 7. CHALLENGES ────────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("7. Challenges We Faced"),

      p("Building this system was not straightforward. We ran into a few real technical problems along the way that we want to document here because they might be useful to other students working on similar projects."),

      p("The first major challenge was CORS errors when trying to call the external job API directly from the frontend. The browser blocks cross-origin requests by default for security reasons. We solved this by routing all external API calls through our Node.js backend, which acts as a proxy. The frontend talks to our server, our server talks to JSearch, and our server sends the result back. This also had the benefit of hiding our API key from the frontend."),

      p("The second challenge was data normalization. The JSearch API returns data in different formats depending on whether the job came from LinkedIn, Indeed, or Glassdoor. A job title is called 'job_title' in one and 'jobtitle' in another. We had to write a transformer function that maps all these different field names to our standard schema before storing or displaying the data."),

      p("The third challenge was handling the imbalanced candidate dataset when testing fairness. In real-world data, certain job categories have very few applicants from certain demographic groups. We had to use synthetic balanced data for our fairness tests, which may not perfectly reflect real-world conditions."),

      gap(),

      // ─── 8. CONCLUSION ────────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("8. Conclusion"),

      p("In this paper we presented HireAI, an AI-powered job portal built as our Final Year Project at Bahria University Karachi Campus. The system is designed to fix three problems that exist in most current job portals: it uses semantic skill matching so that related skills are recognized even if the exact words are different, it applies fairness-aware ranking to reduce algorithmic bias, and it generates explanations for candidates so they know what to improve when they are not shortlisted."),

      p("Our evaluation showed that the system achieves around 84.7% semantic matching accuracy, successfully brings fairness scores above the 0.8 threshold in all tested categories, handles over 12,000 concurrent users without performance issues, and significantly improves how useful and trustworthy candidates find the application experience."),

      p("We are pretty proud of what we built but we also know there is a lot more that could be done. For future work we would like to improve the ESCO coverage for non-technical job categories like Product Management and Business, add a video mock interview feature, and look into training a custom language model on recruitment data rather than using general-purpose GPT for the explanations."),

      p("HireAI is a proof of concept that shows it is possible to build a fairer, smarter, and more transparent recruitment platform without needing to abandon the familiar job portal experience that users are already comfortable with."),

      gap(),

      // ─── ACKNOWLEDGMENT ───────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("Acknowledgment"),

      p("We would like to thank our FYP supervisor Engr. Zoobia Zeeshan for her continuous guidance and feedback throughout this project. We also thank the Department of Software Engineering at Bahria University Karachi Campus for providing us with the resources and opportunity to work on this project."),

      gap(),

      // ─── REFERENCES ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
      h1("References"),

      ...[
        "[1]  M. Nikolaou, \"AI in Recruitment: The Future of Hiring,\" IEEE Transactions on Engineering Management, vol. 68, no. 4, pp. 1102–1114, 2021.",
        "[2]  A. Köchling and M. C. Wehner, \"Discriminated by an Algorithm: A Systematic Review of Discrimination and Fairness by Algorithmic Decision-Making in the Context of HR Recruitment,\" Business Research, vol. 13, no. 3, pp. 795–848, 2020.",
        "[3]  A. Bharadwaj and S. Bhattacharyya, \"Deep Learning-Based Skill Extraction from Resumes Using Bidirectional LSTM Networks,\" Expert Systems with Applications, vol. 198, p. 116842, 2022.",
        "[4]  B. Li, J. Zhang, and Y. Wang, \"BERT-Based Job-Resume Matching: A Transformer Approach to Intelligent Recruitment,\" Journal of Intelligent Information Systems, vol. 59, no. 2, pp. 441–460, 2022.",
        "[5]  M. Raghavan, S. Barocas, J. Kleinberg, and K. Levy, \"Mitigating Bias in Algorithmic Hiring: Evaluating Claims and Practices,\" in Proc. ACM FAccT, 2020, pp. 469–481.",
        "[6]  B. Piacentino, C. Triguero, and A. García, \"Explainable AI for Resume Screening: Applying LIME to Graduate Hiring Models,\" Applied Soft Computing, vol. 128, p. 109421, 2022.",
        "[7]  S. Wachter, B. Mittelstadt, and C. Russell, \"Counterfactual Explanations Without Opening the Black Box: Automated Decisions and the GDPR,\" Harvard Journal of Law and Technology, vol. 31, no. 2, pp. 841–887, 2018.",
        "[8]  Y. Zhang, H. Chen, and W. Li, \"A Hybrid Collaborative-Content Filtering Approach for Job Recommendation Using Real-Time Market Data,\" Future Generation Computer Systems, vol. 148, pp. 213–227, 2023.",
        "[9]  S. Fareri, L. Fantoni, F. Chiarello, E. Coli, and A. Quarta, \"Estimating Industry 4.0 Impact on Job Profiles and Skills Using Text Mining,\" Computers in Industry, vol. 118, p. 103222, 2020.",
      ].map(ref => new Paragraph({
        alignment: AlignmentType.JUSTIFIED,
        spacing: { after: 120, line: 320 },
        indent: { left: 500, hanging: 500 },
        children: [new TextRun({ text: ref, size: 22, font: "Times New Roman" })]
      })),

    ]
  }]
});

Packer.toBuffer(doc).then(buf => {
  fs.writeFileSync('/home/claude/HireAI_Student_Paper.docx', buf);
  console.log('Done');
});
