      body("The XAI Engine implements counterfactual explanation generation for all match scores. Given a candidate's current score and the gap to the minimum requirement threshold, the engine identifies the minimal set of skill additions that would produce a meaningful (≥10 percentage point) score increase. The algorithm computes feature-level contribution of each skill dimension using a simplified SHAP decomposition over the skill embedding space. Missing skills are ranked by their marginal contribution to a hypothetically improved score. The top 3 actionable improvements are formatted into natural language using GPT-4o-mini, grounded in specific named skill acquisitions rather than abstract advice."),

      ...gap(1),
      algoXAI(),
      ...gap(1),

      h2("D.  Resume Analyzer and ATS Scoring"),
      body("The Resume Analyzer accepts PDF and DOCX files. PyMuPDF handles text extraction from PDF documents, python-docx processes DOCX files, and Tesseract OCR provides fallback processing for scanned or image-based PDFs. Extracted text flows through a SpaCy NLP pipeline: sentence tokenization, Named Entity Recognition for personal information extraction, and a custom skill extraction component fine-tuned on software engineering and business administration resume datasets."),
      body("ATS score is a weighted composite across five dimensions: skills match (40%), experience relevance (25%), education alignment (20%), resume structural compliance (10%), and keyword density (5%). Each component is scored independently and accompanied by specific, actionable improvement recommendations — directly addressing the opacity problem of commercial ATS systems."),

      ...gap(1),
      algoATS(),
      ...gap(1),

      h2("E.  Hybrid Job Discovery Engine"),
      body("The Hybrid Job Discovery Engine operates in two user-selectable modes. **Internal Mode** queries MongoDB for employer-posted jobs fully integrated with ATS scoring and fairness-aware ranking. **External Mode** queries the JSearch API aggregating listings from LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor. In External Mode, the backend acts as a transparent proxy: it forwards search parameters to JSearch, receives normalized JSON, applies a field transformation layer (e.g., job_title → title, employer_name → company), and returns identical job card data structures to the frontend. Applying to external listings redirects users to the original platform posting URL."),

      h2("F.  AI Career Chatbot"),
      body("The chatbot is implemented as a floating widget available on all authenticated pages, powered by GPT-class LLM APIs with HuggingFace Inference API fallback for cost management. A carefully engineered system prompt injects live user context: current profile completion status, active application states, ATS score results, and identified skill gaps. The chatbot supports career guidance, platform navigation assistance, and mock interview preparation with structured feedback. Conversation history is maintained client-side in Redux state and included in each API request to preserve multi-turn context."),

      // ══ V. IMPLEMENTATION ══
      h1("V.  Implementation"),

      h2("A.  Development Environment"),
      body("Development was conducted on Windows 11 workstations using Visual Studio Code with ESLint and Prettier for code quality enforcement. Node.js v20 LTS served the backend; Python 3.11 with virtual environment isolation served the AI microservice. Docker containerized the Python microservice during integration testing. Git with GitHub provided version control following a structured branching strategy with mandatory peer review via pull requests."),

      h2("B.  Database Design"),
      body("MongoDB Atlas schema comprises five primary collections. The **Users** collection employs a polymorphic design with role-discriminated embedded subdocuments: job seekers embed resume content and skill arrays, while employers embed company references and subscription metadata. The **Jobs** collection distinguishes internal from external (JSearch-origin) records through a source field. The **Applications** collection maintains full lifecycle state through explicit status transitions (Applied → Reviewed → Shortlisted → Interviewed → Offered/Rejected) with timestamps. The **Companies** collection is referenced by both Jobs and User employer profiles. The **Sessions** collection maintains a JWT blacklist for cryptographically secure logout."),

      h2("C.  External Integrations"),
      body("JSearch API via RapidAPI serves as the unified aggregation layer for external job listings. The backend proxy normalizes response schemas through a transformer function mapping JSearch field names to HireAI's internal job schema, ensuring frontend components receive consistent data structures regardless of listing origin. LinkedIn and Google OAuth 2.0 enable single-sign-on authentication. Cloudinary provides cloud file storage for resumes and company logos with automatic format conversion and global CDN delivery."),

      // Fig 6
      imgPlaceholder("6", "Employer Dashboard — Candidate Ranking List with ATS Scores and Bias Audit Chart"),
      figCaption("Fig. 6. Employer dashboard: fairness-aware candidate ranking with demographic parity annotations and bias audit summary."),

      // ══ VI. TESTING AND RESULTS ══
      h1("VI.  Testing and Results"),

      h2("A.  Testing Strategy"),
      body("Testing followed a three-tier strategy: unit testing of individual modules, integration testing of cross-component API interactions, and User Acceptance Testing with real end users in structured task scenarios. Unit tests used Jest with Supertest for Node.js backend components, achieving 80% code coverage on controllers and authentication middleware. The Python AI microservice used pytest with fixture-based test data covering normal inputs, edge cases (empty resumes, malformed PDFs), and adversarial inputs."),

      h2("B.  User Acceptance Testing"),
      body("UAT involved 10 job seeker participants (Bahria University engineering students) and 3 employer participants (HR managers from Pakistani technology companies). Participants completed structured task lists without researcher guidance, simulating real-world independent usage. A post-task questionnaire measured comprehension, efficiency, and satisfaction on 5-point Likert scales. Key findings: 9 of 10 job seekers rated the ATS score and improvement suggestions as clear and actionable (4.2/5.0 mean). 8 of 10 found the XAI explanation helpful in understanding match score rationale, meeting the 80% comprehension target. All 3 employer participants reported AI-assisted candidate ranking was significantly more time-efficient than their current manual screening processes."),

      h2("C.  Performance Results"),
      tableCaption("Table III.  System Performance Results Against Defined Targets"),
      makeTableII(),
      ...gap(1),

      h2("D.  AI Module Results"),
      tableCaption("Table IV.  AI Module Evaluation Results"),
      makeTableIII(),
      ...gap(1),

      // Fig 7
      imgPlaceholder("7", "Results Visualization — Bar/Radar Chart: All 6 AI Metrics vs. Their Targets"),
      figCaption("Fig. 7. AI module performance: achieved results against defined targets across all six evaluation metrics."),

      // ══ VII. DISCUSSION ══
      h1("VII.  Discussion"),
      body("The empirical results validate HireAI's core architectural hypotheses. The 87.3% semantic matching accuracy, achieved through ESCO taxonomy integration and transformer-based embeddings, confirms that vocabulary mismatch is tractable with currently available NLP infrastructure. The 13-percentage-point improvement over the 74% baseline of pure TF-IDF matching (measured on the same test set) quantifies the practical value of semantic approaches."),
      body("The 0.83 demographic parity ratio demonstrates that post-processing fairness-aware ranking achieves meaningful bias mitigation without requiring protected attribute collection or retraining the core matching model. The approach's modularity — fairness correction applied only at ranking, not during semantic matching — preserves the accuracy of the Semantic Intelligence Engine while satisfying the Four-Fifths Rule threshold."),
      body("The 80% XAI comprehension rate from UAT is both a validation and a design learning. It confirms that counterfactual explanations — framed as specific skill acquisition recommendations with projected score impact — successfully translate technical matching logic into guidance that non-technical users understand and find actionable. The 20% who did not fully comprehend the explanations were primarily unfamiliar with ESCO skill taxonomy terminology, not the explanation format itself — suggesting that simplifying skill naming would improve comprehension further."),
      body("The Hybrid Job Discovery Engine's architecture demonstrates a generalizable pattern for platform integration in fragmented domains: normalized proxy aggregation allows a unified user experience without requiring direct partnership agreements with incumbent platforms."),

      // ══ VIII. LIMITATIONS AND FUTURE WORK ══
      h1("VIII.  Limitations and Future Work"),
      body("Several limitations bound the current system's applicability. **ESCO taxonomy coverage** is optimized for European and Western labor markets; Pakistani-specific skill terminology, particularly for informal sector occupations and local industry roles, has substantially lower coverage. The embedding-based fallback provides partial mitigation, but systematic evaluation of local market coverage gaps remains a priority for future work."),
      body("The **Fairness-Aware Ranking module** infers protected attribute proxies rather than collecting self-reported demographic data, introducing potential measurement inaccuracy. Proxy inference from language patterns is known to produce errors, particularly for South Asian names. Future work should explore privacy-preserving demographic feedback mechanisms that enable more accurate fairness measurement without requiring sensitive data disclosure."),
      body("**UAT sample size** (10 job seekers, 3 employers) is sufficient for formative evaluation but insufficient for statistical generalization. A larger-scale longitudinal evaluation across age groups, educational backgrounds, and industry sectors would strengthen the evidence base."),
      body("Planned future development includes: AI video mock interview modules with real-time speech analysis; salary prediction using aggregated market data; e-learning integration with Coursera and Udemy for direct skill gap remediation; Pakistani-specific taxonomy expansion; multi-language support including Urdu; and native iOS and Android mobile applications."),

